Solve the equation $-2(3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}=-54$ for the variable $x$.
\begin{align*}
\text{A)}\ & x=9 &
\text{B)}\ & x=\frac{5}{6} \\
\text{C)}\ & x=\frac{23}{6} &
\text{D)}\ & x=\frac{7}{3} \\
\end{align*}    
\end{problem}
\noindent

meta-llama/Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct_respons:
Reasoning: To solve the given equation, we start by isolating the term with the exponent. 

\begin{align*}
-2(3x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}&=-54\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (3x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}&=27
\end{align*}
Next, we take both sides to the power of $\frac{2}{3}$ to get rid of the exponent.
\begin{align*}
(3x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}&=27\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3x+2&=(27)^{\frac{2}{3}}=9\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3x&=9-2=7\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{7}{3}
\end{align*}
So, the solution to the equation is $x=\frac{7}{3}$.

### Answer: D)  $\boxed{\frac{7}{3}}$

