Evaluate the improper integral $\displaystyle{\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{x^2+2x+2}dx}$.
\end{problem}
\noindent

meta-llama/Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct_respons:
To evaluate the improper integral $\displaystyle{\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{x^2+2x+2}dx}$, we first complete the square in the denominator:

\begin{align*}
x^2+2x+2 &= (x+1)^2+1\\
&=(x+1)^2+\left(\sqrt{1}\right)^2\\
&=(x+1)^2+1^2
\end{align*}

Then, we can rewrite the integral as follows:

\begin{align*}
\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{x^2+2x+2}dx &= \int_0^\infty \frac{1}{(x+1)^2+1^2}dx
\end{align*}

Next, we can use the trigonometric substitution $x+1 = \tan \theta$ to simplify the integral. Note that $dx = \sec^2 \theta d\theta$, and when $x = 0$, $\theta = 0$, and when $x = \infty$, $\theta = \frac{\pi}{2}$. Therefore, we have:

\begin{align*}
\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{(x+1)^2+1^2}dx &= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{\sec^2 \theta}{\tan^2 \theta + 1}d\theta\\
&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{\sec^2 \theta}{\sec^2 \theta}d\theta\\
&= \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} 1 d\theta\\
&= \left[\theta\right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\\
&= \frac{\pi}{2}-0\\
&= \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*}

