To evaluate the iterated integral, we first integrate with respect to x and then with respect to y.

\begin{align*}
\int_0^1dy\int_y^1(e^{-x^2}+e^x)dx&=\int_0^1dy\left[\int_y^1e^{-x^2}dx+\int_y^1e^xdx\right]\\
&=\int_0^1dy\left[\int_y^1e^{-x^2}dx+\left(e^x\right)\bigg|_y^1\right]\\
&=\int_0^1dy\left[\int_y^1e^{-x^2}dx+e^x-e^y\right]\\
&=\int_0^1\left[\int_y^1e^{-x^2}dx+e^x-e^y\right]dy
\end{align*}

Now, we can change the order of integration. To do this, we need to change the limits of integration for the inner integral. When y = 0, x can range from 0 to 1, and when y = 1, x can range from 1 to 1.

\begin{align*}
\int_0^1\left[\int_y^1e^{-x^2}dx+e^x-e^y\right]dy&=\int_0^1\left[e^{-x^2}\right]_{x=0}^{x=y}dy+\int_0^1e^xdy-\int_0^1e^ydy\\
&=\int_0^1\left(e^{-y^2}-1\right)dy+\left(e^x\right)\bigg|_0^1-\left(e^y\right)\bigg|_0^1\\
&=\int_0^1\left(e^{-y^2}-1\right)dy+e^1-e^0-e^1+e^0\\
&=\int_0^1\left(e^{-y^2}-1\right)dy
\end{align*}

Now, we can evaluate the integral.

\begin{align*}
\int_0^1\left(e^{-y^2}-1\right)dy&=\left[-\frac{1}{2}e^{-y^2}\right]_0^1-\left[y\right]_0^1\\
&=-\frac{1}{2}e^{-1}-\frac{1}{2}+1\\
&=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}e^{-1}
\end{align*}

