\lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 - k^2}} &= \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x_k^2}} \cdot \Delta x \\
&= \int_{0}^{1} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}} \, dx.
\end{align*}
Now, we can evaluate the integral:
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}} \, dx &= \arcsin x \Big|_{0}^{1} \\
&= \arcsin 1 - \arcsin 0 \\
&= \frac{\pi}{2} - 0 \\
&= \boxed{\frac{\pi}{2}}.
\end{align*}
### Answer: $\boxed{\frac{\pi}{2}}$

