What values of x make the inequality true? $4(x-2)-10x\geq -3x+13$
\begin{align*}
\text{A)}\ & \{x: x\geq 1\} &
\text{B)}\ & \{x: x\geq -7\}\\
\text{C)}\ & \{x: x\leq 1\}  &
\text{D)}\ & \{x: x\leq -7\}\\
\end{align*} 
\end{problem}
\noindent

meta-llama/Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct_respons:
To solve the inequality, we need to simplify the expression first.

\begin{align*}
4(x-2)-10x &\geq -3x+13\\
4x-8-10x &\geq -3x+13\\
-6x-8 &\geq -3x+13
\end{align*}

Next, we move all the terms to one side of the inequality to isolate $x$.

\begin{align*}
-6x-8 &\geq -3x+13\\
-6x+3x &\geq 13+8\\
-3x &\geq 21
\end{align*}

Now, we divide both sides by $-3$ to solve for $x$. Remember that when we divide or multiply an inequality by a negative number, we need to flip the direction of the inequality.

\begin{align*}
-3x &\geq 21\\
x &\leq -7
\end{align*}

Therefore, the solution to the inequality is $\{x: x\leq -7\}$.

### Answer: D

